I then tested whether pairs of features showed subgroup heterogeneity or interaction on the response-probability scale. Binary variables used 1 vs 0, while multi-valued variables used above-median vs at-or-below-median groups for adequate cell sizes. For each pair, the effect estimate was the four-cell difference-in-differences: response(high,high) - response(high,low) - response(low,high) + response(low,low). Positive values mean the joint high/present subgroup responded more than expected from the separate feature effects; negative values mean less than expected. The strongest pairwise interaction results were:
